Project: Prosper Loan Data¶

by Eleftherios Kokkinis¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this project, we will be analyzing Loan Data from the Prosper peer-to-peer lending markeplace.

Our goal is to determine important factors that can affect the status of a loan (Defaulted,Completed,Charged off) as well as the score that it gets from Prosper, ProsperScore. Finally we will look into what factors may affect the APR of the Borrowers as well as the size of the loans.

First we intent to wrangle and clean some of the issues that our data may have. Then we will pose some questions which we will attempt to answer by performing exploratory data analysis practices and creating several visualizations.

Dataset Overview¶

Our dataset contains information for about 114.000 loans and 84 different features for each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

Loan Status¶

As we can see below in the barplot below, the most common Loan Status is Current, at 55000 loans, with Completed and Chargedoff following at 37000 and 12000 respectively. The Defaulted loans account for 5000 of the loans.

In [977]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
sb.barplot(y=df.LoanStatus.value_counts(),x=df.LoanStatus.value_counts().index);
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.title('Amount of Loans per Status')
plt.ylabel('Loan counts')
plt.xlabel('Status');

Listing Categories¶

We will now check which categories are the most common ones among the loans

In [978]:
 # Listing Category

plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))

It is made clear that most loans are for Debt Consolidation, with the 'Other' category following up before the Home improvements and the Business. We will now proceed by checking the EmploymentStatus and the IncomeRanges.

EmploymentStatus - IncomeRange¶

In the graphs below, we can observe that the majority of the loans were given to Income groups (yearly) 25.000-49.000 and 50.000-74.999. While the overwhelming majority of those who took a loan were Employed.

We will now proceed by taking a look into the relations between Categorical and Numerical Variables

Loan Amount - Listing Categories, Employment Status and Loan Status¶

We will check through violinplots how the total Loan amount is related to specific categorical variables

In [983]:
violinplots(df,['ListingCategory','EmploymentStatus','LoanStatus','IncomeRange'],'LoanOriginalAmount')

In all the violin plots, we are able to spot that the big bulk of the Loan Amounts goes up to 15000. However, larger amounts seem to be given for Debt Consolidation. In addtion, people with Employed and Full-Time status are also more likely to receive higher amount loans.

The LoanStatus do not seem particularly related to the Loan Amount, although the 'Current' status includes more Loans of higher amounts. Finally, the higher income groups seem to also be getting higher loan amounts which is a rather reasonable observation.

Checking relation between APR, State and ProsperScore¶

In [986]:
boxplots(df,['BorrowerState','ProsperScore'])

Generally, the APR does not look particularly affected by the State of origin of the borrower. However, the states of Maine and Iowa seem to be getting a lower APR overall.

The interesting but expected observation here is that loans with higher ProsperScore are getting a visibly lower APR, while loans with lower score a significantly higher APR. That's reasonable considering that the ProsperScore is also a reflection of the risk that each loan entails.

Checking how ProsperScore is related to Income Range and Loan Status¶

In [987]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))

plt.subplot(2,1,1)
sb.countplot(data=df,x='ProsperScore',hue='IncomeRange');
plt.legend(loc=2, prop={'size': 10})
plt.title('ProsperScores per Income Group')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.2)

ax=plt.subplot(2,1,2)
sb.countplot(data=df,x='ProsperScore',hue='LoanStatus')
plt.legend(loc=1, prop={'size': 9})
plt.title('ProsperScores per Loan Status');

Obersvations:

  • The higher we move to ProsperScores, the more likely it becomes to encounter higher income groups and vice versa.
  • The higher we move to ProsperScores, the less likely it becomes to encounter Past Due, Defaulted or Chargedoff loans.

The ProsperScores seem to be a good reflection of the risk that some loans entail.

Prosper Score in relation to Borrower APR and Loan Amount¶

In [988]:
sb.relplot(data=df,x='LoanOriginalAmount',y='BorrowerAPR',hue='ProsperScore');
plt.title('ProsperScore in relation to APR and Loan Amount');

We can see here again, that lower APR translates to higher Proper Score. In addition, we can see observe the negative relation between APR and Loan Amount. Higher Loan amounts equal to a lower APR and overall a higher Prosper Score.

Income Ranges in relation to APR and Loan amounts¶

Now we will explore in the same manner how the different income groups relate to APR and loan sizes.

In [989]:
sb.relplot(data=df,x='LoanOriginalAmount',y='BorrowerAPR',hue='IncomeRange');
plt.title('Income Range in relation to APR and Loan Amount');

We can verify here the positive relation between higher loans and higher income ranges, which again makes sense.

ProsperScore in relation to EstimatedLoss and APR¶

Finally we will check the positive relation that we found between APR and EstimatedLoss, and both of them will be compared to ProsperScores

In [992]:
sb.relplot(data=df,x='EstimatedLoss',y='BorrowerAPR',hue='ProsperScore');
plt.title('Prosper Score in relation to APR and EstimatedLoss');

It is evident that the lower the EstimatedScore, the lower the APR is. Simultaneously, lower Estimated Scores and APRs translate to a higher Prosper Score. So we can conclude that these are rather good factors in determining the Prosper Score.

LoanStatus and Prosper Score in relation to Estimated Loss¶

As a final insight, we will check the relation between Estimated Loss, Proper Score and the status of the loans.

As we can see below, the loans wish small Estimated loss featured a higher Prosper Score as we saw earlier. But in addition to that, we are now able to see that the loans with the status of Defaulted, Completed and Changed off also featured a higher Estimated Loss and consequently a lower Prosper Score than the rest.

In [991]:
sb.catplot(x="LoanStatus", y="EstimatedLoss", hue="ProsperScore", data=df)
plt.xticks(rotation=90);
